{
  "texts": [
    "7:Compute gradients (∇ A1 loss i, ∇ B1 loss i) using backward-pass on the student model.",
    "8:Update A 1, B 1 using the gradients∇W L ΦStd = 1 |B| i∈B ∇ W loss i, ∀W ∈ {A 1, B 1 }.9: end for Output: {A 1, B 1 } and fine-tuned weights of the student model:W Std = W pretrain Std + A 1 * B 1.Given an input sample x i, the knowledge distillation (KD) loss of the student model f ΦStd with respect to the teacher model f ΦStd is given byℓ KD [z i Std, z i Tch] = KL[ σ(z i Std /t), σ(z i Tch /t)],where σ(•) denotes the soft-max operation, KL[•, •] denotes the standard KL divergence between two probability vectors, and t ≥ 1 is called the KD temperature.",
    "Given input x i, let h iStd:= (h i,1 Std,..., h i,l Std,...) denote the feature vectors from all transformer layers of the student model with h i,l Std being the feature vector from l-th layer.",
    "Now, we define the feature based distillation loss asℓ FD [h i Std, h i Tch] = l β l ∥U l Std h i,l Std -U l Tch h i,g(l) Tch ∥ 2 2,where the summation l is over (a subset of) the layers of the student model, {β l ≥ 0} are user chosen constants, ∥ • ∥ 2 denotes the Euclidean norm, and the function g maps each layer index l of the student model to a layer index g(l) of the teacher model for comparing corresponding features.",
    "The projection matrices {U l Std, U l Tch } are simultaneously learned along with the LoRA weights and are needed to compare the feature vectors from the student with those from the teacher by projecting them to a common low-dimensional space."
  ]
}